"# Appendix 2 — Top 10 language features (the wow layer)

<!-- covers-through: 2026-07-11 -->

The ten features that make Sakura Scheme feel modern. Each: description + runnable example + how to invoke from REPL, cart, or Cortex.

---

## 1. Native pattern matching (`match`)

Destructures lists, records, and keyword-arg forms; compiles to nested `cond`.

```scheme
(match value
  [(list 'point x y) (draw x y)]
  [(record card :id id :kind k) (open-card id k)]
  [(list :cmd 'move :dx dx :dy dy) (move dx dy)]
  [_ (log :level 'warn :event 'unmatched)])
```

**Invoke:** REPL, cart, Cortex. Also see 15.1 for view/or/and/guard extensions.

## 2. Keyword + optional arguments

Verbs opt-in to `:name value` kwargs with defaults. The interpreter reads `:foo` as a keyword literal.

```scheme
(define (greet who :greeting \"hi\" :loud? #f)
  (let ([msg (string-append greeting \", \" who)])
    (if loud? (string-upcase msg) msg)))

(greet \"sakura\")                       ; -> \"hi, sakura\"
(greet \"sakura\" :greeting \"hello\")     ; -> \"hello, sakura\"
(greet \"sakura\" :loud? #t)             ; -> \"HI, SAKURA\"
```

## 3. Destructuring in `let` and `lambda`

```scheme
(let ([(x y z) some-list]) (+ x y z))

((lambda ([:name n :age a]) (list n a)) :name \"sakura\" :age 4)
```

## 4. Async / await

First-class, JS Promises under the hood.

```scheme
(let ([data (await (fetch \"https://api.example/thing\"))])
  (log :level 'info :event 'fetched :bytes (string-length data))
  data)
```

## 5. Records with generated getters

`define-record` produces the predicate, constructor, and per-field getter. Slat serialization is automatic.

```scheme
(define-record point (x y))
(define p (make-point 3 4))
(point? p)      ; -> #t
(point-x p)     ; -> 3
(point-y p)     ; -> 4
(slat/save p)   ; -> serializable
```

## 6. First-class types

Every value carries a runtime type tag; `describe` prints type + fields + doc.

```scheme
(type-of 42)                ; -> 'number
(type-of 'sakura)           ; -> 'symbol
(type-of (make-point 3 4))  ; -> 'point
(describe (make-point 3 4)) ; -> full field + doc render
```

## 7. Modules with import/export

```scheme
(module physics-helpers
  (export gravity settle)
  (define gravity 9.81)
  (define (settle v damping) (* v damping)))

(import physics-helpers :as p)
(p/settle 10 0.9)
```

## 8. Rich error records

Slat forms with `:kind`, `:message`, `:source-pos`, `:did-you-mean`, `:fix`, `:examples`; catchable via `guard`.

```scheme
(guard (err [(and (record? err) (eq? (error-kind err) 'arity-mismatch))
             (log :level 'warn :event 'arity :verb (error-verb err))
             (sakura/fix err)])
  (some-verb 'wrong 'args))
```

## 9. Lazy sequences / streams

```scheme
(define naturals (stream-iterate (lambda (n) (+ n 1)) 1))
(stream-take naturals 5)  ; -> (1 2 3 4 5)
```

## 10. Contract-checked verbs

The dispatcher enforces `:contract` — wrong-type arg errors *before* the impl runs, with a structured error.

```scheme
(env.define 'motion/hop hop-impl
  :arity [1 2]
  :contract '(-> entity? (or/c number? void?) entity?)
  :doc \"Hop the entity by dy (default 1).\")

(motion/hop \"not-an-entity\")
; -> #<error :kind 'contract :verb 'motion/hop :expected 'entity? :got 'string>
```

## Feature dispatch table

| Feature | Reader | Interpreter | Metadata | Where to look |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| match | – | compiler | `:contract` uses | `src/interp.js:match` |
| kwargs | reader | dispatcher | `:arity [min max :keys ...]` | `src/dispatch.js` |
| destructuring | reader | binder | – | `src/interp.js:bind` |
| async/await | – | scheduler | `:async? #t` | `src/interp.js:await` |
| records | – | – | `:record` decl | `src/interp.js:record` |
| type-of | – | value tags | `:type` | `src/base.js:type-of` |
| modules | – | resolver | `:module` | `src/interp.js:module` |
| errors | – | throw path | `:error` shape | `src/base.js:error` |
| streams | – | thunks | – | `src/base.js:stream-*` |
| contracts | – | dispatcher | `:contract` | `src/dispatch.js:enforce` |
")
